         <abstract>
            <p>Textbooks are agreed that evaluation of a prospective investment project in terms of its net present value provides a meaningful assessment of the project's ability to contribute to shareholder wealth if certain conditions obtain. That the project be financed according to the firm's current (and presumably target) market-value debt-equity ratio numbers among these conditions, supposedly ensuring that ratio's constancy as use of the net present value investment criterion requires. Reconsideration of the problem reveals that raising funds in this manner alters the market-value debt-equity ratio and causes the net present value computation to overstate the shareholder gain. This article formulates a financial policy that does not subvert the rationale underlying the net present value investment criterion.</p>
         </abstract>
